snippet.textDisplay:
Formula 1 ultimately ended for me with the halo cars. My opinion of the whole matter is that if safety is #1 then have horses pull the car around the track and have the drivers sit in the pits while they steer the cars with a remote control.
Racing is supposed to be exciting and involve the element of danger. Halos make F1 an ugly thing to look at and remove the driver even further from the fans.
The turbo v6 hybrid drivetrains were the 2nd from the final nail in the coffin for me. Crazy V8, v10, and v12 engines screaming to 20,000+ rpm....that's exciting. Not the current shit-show that F1 is now.
VW, another shit-show corporation saddled down with horrible, bloated management ruining the best efforts of excellent engineers.

snippet.textDisplay:
Why is there a B in MEB? Or in MQB? Or in MLB?
The secret is: folks at VW speak German.

MEB = Modularer Elektrik Baukasten.
Baukasten = construction kit.

And "V" is pronounced like "F" in German. So it's "Folkswagen". ;)
snippet.textOriginal:
Why is there a B in MEB? Or in MQB? Or in MLB?
The secret is: folks at VW speak German.

MEB = Modularer Elektrik Baukasten.
Baukasten = construction kit.

And "V" is pronounced like "F" in German. So it's "Folkswagen". ;)

snippet.textDisplay:
It will hurt them, but I think the way it’s broadcasted hurts F1 more. I grew up watching F1 when it was free on TV. I’m a fan for over 30 years. Enjoy it and pay for it, but if I was an 8 year old I would probably not discover it like I did as a kid. I think sky sports offers a good service, but the overall stuff that Will Buxton and his team do for the Youtube channel is good enough. And I’m not sure what the sponsorship value is if you have a limited audience in subscription models.

I watch some FE and Indycar and honestly there is good racing, but I like the fact F1 isn’t a full spec series. The cars are more interesting.

I think Liberty are doing a good job, but let’s see if it pays off.

As a kid I liked F1 as they said the cats had more uncommon with fighter jets rather than road cars. To be honest the more comparisons they make F1 cars to road cars the more lame the series looks.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm not as worried about this because of business reasons actually. I know a lot of people are going to say F1 and FE are very different things (which is true). But the fact is that the budget that goes into funding most car companies' racing arms (the only notable exception I'm aware of being Toyota) is NOT from the companies' R+D budget: it comes out of their MARKETING budget. So when you see the number that Mercedes put half a billion dollars into their F1 program last year? That money isn't coming out of battery and composites research, it's coming out of ads. As long as Mercedes can put on a compelling performance in a racing series with enough eyes on it that doesn't generate any negative publicity (IE with obvious safety or environmental issues) and that sells them more cars than the additional ads they could otherwise buy, it is worth it for them to continue spending that money on racing. And with F1, they get all sorts of press right now because they've put Louis Hamilton in a position to match or break the record of the winningest driver in F1 history and the team has won the last half decade of drivers and constructors championships in a show of dominance which has never been seen before. If that's not solid marketing, I don't know what is.

snippet.textDisplay:
One problem, bo. A performance electric motor needs a battery. A BIG BIG battery and lots of them in order to maintain performance. 20km sure, 50km maybe, 100 uhh no. They don't have the range and they're heavy. Very very heavy. Batteries are SO SO SO far away from providing the kind of power able to maintain the speed of a race car. On the same line, just look at the now fairly mature electric cars. Three hundred miles is a dream if you run flat roads with no head winds and all sorts of other big failures. Now everybody is all about superchargin those cars up while you stop but the fact is that a full supercharge if you happen to have anybody beside you is one and a half hours. Some people can refuel their pickup trucks in under three minutes.

Gas engines aren't going anywhere. Ten years maybe but right now, battery and battery technology is just not moving forward very quickly for a number of reasons. Lithium? It doesn't get mined from many places. The whole Lithium type of battery itself is questioned as probably not being the best material for these batteries unless they find better ways to make them. Lastly, these things need to remain CHEAP. You cannot fill the bottom of a car with Lithium batteries for cheaper than you can build a gasoline fed car. This isn't going to change because lithium is being used in EVERYTHING now.

Anyways, a good post if your head is in the clouds and you're not talking about being factually correct or physically possible for over ten years buuut it's just not going to go down like that.
